<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900727-0127</DOCNO><DOCID>900727-0127.</DOCID><HL>   Stock-Index Arbitrage Tops   50% of Program Trading</HL><DATE>07/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   GE MS Z.CSU</CO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Stock-index arbitrage accounted for more thanhalf of total program trading volume during the week of July9 through 13, the New York Stock Exchange said yesterday.   Stock-index arbitrage, the most controversial form ofprogram trading, in which traders jump between stock-indexfutures and options and underlying stocks to lock in profits,accounted for 52.9% of all program trades during July 9through 13. The previous week, stock-index arbitrageaccounted for 45% of all program trading.</LP><TEXT>   The Big Board said that of the top five program-tradingfirms for the week, about 79% of all index arbitrage wasconducted by General Electric Co.'s Kidder, Peabody andamp; Co.unit, Morgan Stanley Group Inc.'s Morgan Stanley andamp; Co. unit,Susquehanna Investment Group and CS First Boston Inc.'s FirstBoston Corp. unit.   Aside from stock-index arbitrage, program trading alsodescribes strategies that involve the purchase or sale ofbaskets of 15 or more stocks.   Overall, program trading amounted to 7.9% of average dailyvolume of 171.3 million shares on the Big Board during theweek, down from 10.9% of average daily volume of 125.1million shares the previous week.</TEXT></DOC>